title: Christmas Ugly Sweater Social :)
description: It is the end of the year! We want to thank our lovely ladies and gents for joining us to make our first few months spectacularly successful! Please join us for a fun social. Location TBD - Ugly sweaters are encouraged but not necessary :) anything christmasy would be fun!

title: November R-Ladies meeting: Technology and the Data Revolution Discussion
description:
Technology and the Data Revolution Discussion, led by Dr Morgan Ernest.
Dr Ernest is a professor at the University of Florida at Wildlife Ecology and Conservation. Her lab is part of the "weecology" group, an interdisciplinary ecology research group (https://www.weecology.org/).
For R-Ladies, she will lead a discussion on how different types of technology are changing the amount of data we have, how we collect it and the challenges these different data types present for analysis/management, etc. This promises to be an interesting discussion considering all our different backgrounds!

If time (and attendance) allows, we also want to do "speed discussions" in small groups, along the lines of speed dating. The idea is that within a set amount of time people talk to each other in small groups or one-on-one about their interests, how they use data and how they use R. When time is up, we change groups. We think this will be a fun way to get to know each other better, and learn more about what's possible in data science and R!

NB We get a $0.50 discount on beers! Meeting will be in the Brick Room. As usual, opportunity to socialize afterwards, and kids are welcome!
Sorry - as far as we're aware there will not be a food truck that evening.

title: Website creation in R: blogdown
description:
It's time for another R-Ladies get-together! We will be having another hands-on meeting, so bring your laptops and power cords! Justin Millar will take us through the steps to create your own website using blogdown in R.
Some examples of R websites:
http://nelson.rbind.io/
https://www.lucymcgowan.com/
http://www.emilyzabor.com/
https://haoye.us/

We expect the meeting to take about an hour but you can stay and socialize, or continue working on your code and websites together.
Children and partners are always welcome at our meetings.

NOTE: location changed to Alachua County Library (Downtown Gainesville). In the Foundation Room!

Dr Auriel Fournier (Twitter: @RallidaeRule) will talk to/with us about the package rtweet - a great package to organize Twitter data and manage tweets. Dr Fournier's website: http://aurielfournier.github.io/

title: R-Ladies Gainesville Launch Social
description:
Dear R-Ladies Gainesville members!

We are glad to announce our Launch event! We hope you’ll be able to join us to meet other R-Ladies members, learn more about the this international network and share more about yourself and your R goals. Since it’ll be the first time many of us meet, we’d like to keep it casual and, together, define the course of the Meetups to come! No laptops are required as there will be no coding - this time.

Looking forward to sharing a beeR with you all!

There will be a food truck available (Mayflower Cellars) during the event and folks are welcome to bring their families.

title: Spatial R - introductory workshop
description:
Our December meeting will be extra special! Join us for this introductory workshop lead by Brittany A. Bankovich, from the Center for Spatial Analysis at FWC. After the workshop we will head downtown for an end of the year social! (At Big Top - walking distance from the library)

During the workshop, Brittany will cover importing spatial data, projections and transformations, basic geometric operations (buffering, intersections, clipping, erasing, distance calculations), useful raster operations (reading them in, reclassifying, summarizing raster data using vector data), basic mapping using ggplot and ggmaps, and a brief demonstration of mapping using leaflet (can implement coarse-scale real-time data like weather).

Make sure you have installed this packages before the meeting:
## Geoprocessing tools
library(sp)
library(rgdal)
library(rgeos)
library(raster)
library(dismo)

# Mapping tools
library(maptools)
library(plyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(ggmap)
library(broom)
library(maps)
library(ggsn)
library(sf)
library(rasterVis)

We will meet at the Foundation Room at the library, which means we need you to RSVP. The space is limited in this room. Thanks!

title: Reproducible Research with RStudio and Docker
description:
November R-Ladies Meeting: Reproducible Research with RStudio and Docker
6:30 pm – 8:00 pm

Reproducible data analysis is gaining traction in many scientific fields because it improves collaboration, increases transparency and trust in science, and can make your workflows more efficient. We’ll discuss some of the issues that arise when someone else (or future you) tries to recreate statistical analyses and figures. Then, we’ll use two tools (RStudio and Docker) to create a reproducible data analysis. You are welcome to follow along with the reproducible data analysis tutorial even if you don’t have the following tools installed on your computer.

Please install (or update) these programs prior to the meet-up. We will be at the meet-up location 30 minutes early to troubleshoot installation issues.
1. R
2. RStudio
3. Docker Desktop or Toolbox*

Installation guides

R and RStudio installation guides from Data Carpentry can be found here: https://datacarpentry.org/R-ecology-lesson/index.html#setup_instructions
Open the programs and check for errors.

Docker Desktop installation guides from Cyverse can be found here (Section 2): https://github.com/sanjanasudarshan/container_camp_workshop_2019/blob/master/docker/dockerintro.rst
Test the Docker installation by following Section 2.1.

*Older versions of Mac and Windows may need to install Docker Toolbox instead of Docker Desktop:
https://docs.docker.com/toolbox/toolbox_install_windows/
https://docs.docker.com/toolbox/toolbox_install_mac/

When you install Docker Desktop/Toolbox, you’ll create a Docker Hub username and password. We will use these during the session.

title: Intro to R and RStudio
description:
Join us for this introductory workshop! We will touch on the basics of R, navigating the RStudio IDE and various troubleshooting issues.

If you've never been to our meetings, this is a great chance to come say hi and get started with R.

Please install R and R Studio before the meeting. We will have facilitators available in case you have issues with installation, but it will be easier for us to move on to using R if the software is already installed.

1. Install R: https://cran.r-project.org/
2. Install R Studio (free desktop version): https://rstudio.com/products/rstudio/download/

Please join our Slack channel for questions or installation troubleshooting
https://join.slack.com/t/rladies-gainesville/shared_invite/enQtNDY0Nzk1NDMzMzkzLTc2YjE3MTI1YzFkZmQ3NTQ1MDc1MGJmMWQ4MjA4YzAxOWYyYTU1MzJjNjVmNjY5MWM5MWQ0NWI3MDA4ODUxMjU

R-LADIES IS A WORLDWIDE ORGANIZATION WHOSE MISSION IS TO PROMOTE GENDER DIVERSITY IN THE R COMMUNITY.

The R community suffers from an underrepresentation of minority genders (including but not limited to cis/trans women, trans men, non-binary, genderqueer, agender) in every role and area of participation, whether as leaders, package developers, conference speakers, conference participants, educators, or users.

As a diversity initiative, the mission of R-Ladies is to achieve proportionate representation by encouraging, inspiring, and empowering people of genders currently underrepresented in the R community. R-Ladies’ primary focus, therefore, is on supporting minority gender R enthusiasts to achieve their programming potential, by building a collaborative global network of R leaders, mentors, learners, and developers to facilitate individual and collective progress worldwide.

title: Social!
description:
This month's meeting is a SOCIAL, co-hosted with UF Women in Science and Engineering (WiSE), the Ally Skills Network, UF Society of Women Engineers (SWE), the Society for Advancement of Chicanos/Hispanics and Native Americans in Science (SACNAS) and the Natural Resources Diversity Initiative (NRDI). This is an opportunity to make connections, talk work or research, and just have fun!
We'd love to see you all to catch up; and hear from you what you would like us to focus on in the months ahead. If you've never been to one of our meetings, this your chance to come chat in an informal setting about R-Ladies.

title: Book Club
description:
~~~~~~ Date and Location have been updated! ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Meet us the "The Bull" downtown from 6-8pm

Join us for a book club discussion of Reshma Saujani’s Brave, Not Perfect. Reshma is the founder and CEO of Girls Who Code. In her popular TED Talk, she advocates for girls to learn coding as a way to practice failure and overcome expectations of “perfection”. Her book Brave, Not Perfect expands on these ideas by describing how society promotes perfection, why we should be learning to be brave instead, and how to achieve this goal.

Where to get the book:
Alachua county library has a couple copies
Used and ebooks start at around $12
Free audiobook with an Audible trial through Amazon
We’ve created a book swap here: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1X36YPE4NVvW9JTZp6AxbAhlsfxra8ntdBsZIllkNC2Q/edit#gid=0

Not able to read the book? Here are some alternatives:
Watch the TED Talk: https://www.ted.com/talks/reshma_saujani_teach_girls_bravery_not_perfection?language=en

Read one of the many book reviews
Just read the questions below and come with some ideas!

Discussion questions to get us started:
1. How does the goal of perfection operate as a barrier in your life?
2. Coding is a great tool for practicing failure. What are some other tools you currently or could use?
3. What are some good examples of bravery that you’ve seen in your field or career?

title: Making your code citable
description: Have you ever created a script and wondered how to share it, publish or even keep track of its ownership? Join us for a discussion on how to make your code citable, share your data, manage various repositories and some insight into types of licenses. We will present you with some resources but we welcome all input, ideas and suggestions. We are hoping to create a collaborative file with various resources on this topic

title: R packages - sharing with others and helping yourself
description: Let's make a package! Javi Rudolph will lead this session and hopefully convince you to make your own R package. A brief introduction to basic package structure coupled with some hands-on exercises and examples will lay the foundation for your package-building journey. Start small with a package for your data analysis, dream big. No prior experience with building R packages is necessary (actually, this is very intro level so if you've built a package before you probably know this). Basic familiarity with R language is helpful.

venues.name: Headquarters Library | Alachua County Library District

title: Intro to R Markdown - easy integration of text, code, references, & more
description: Kristen Sauby will introduce the basics of R Markdown, talk about how it's great for the integration of text and code, is very flexible in terms of formatting, and is a great way to automatically number tables and figures and build a list of reference cited. No prior knowledge of R Markdown is necessary, and we'll have tips and tricks for those of all skill levels.

venues.name: Headquarters Library | Alachua County Library District

title: February R-Ladies meeting: Data visualization
description:
Meeting in the Foundation Room (upstairs)

We'll be going over some basics and practicalities when it comes to data visualization (no coding), and then get our hands dirty with some examples of plots, graphs and maps in R. We cover a few of the basics of ggplot2 (R's plotting package that most people use), but will also show some more complicated things you could do.

Feel free to bring your own code and plots to share with the group. We can socialize afterwards, or if you want to talk about your plot during the meeting, please shoot us an email (gainesville [at] rladies [dot] org) so we can slot you in.

venues.name: Headquarters Library | Alachua County Library District

title: January R-Ladies meeting: Juniper Simonis on data and research consulting
description:
Juniper Simonis runs DAPPER Stats, providing consulting services on research and data science (https://www.dapperstats.com/about/). They will talk to us about running a business/consultancy and will try to answer any questions you have!
We will be hosted by the Collaboratory for Women Innovators (http://innovate.research.ufl.edu/the-hub/collaboratory/), located at The Hub at UF Innovate. We will also get some more information on this initiative and there will be an opportunity to interact with people from Collaboratory.

title: Practicing Data Visualization in R
description:
Practice your data wrangling and visualization skills with other members of R-Ladies! During this virtual event, participants will work on this week's Tidy Tuesday dataset.

The R for Data Science Online Learning Community hosts a weekly "Tidy Tuesday" project in which they release a curated dataset every Tuesday for R users to practice data skills.

The dataset will be posted here on Monday (same day as this Meetup): https://github.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/tree/master/data/2020

We hope these meetups will provide a space to interact with other R users and set a time in their calendars to work on the Tidy Tuesday challenge. You can think of these meetups as an accountability tool rather than a class. Each meeting, R-Ladies Gainesville will provide an additional challenge to inspire you in your data visualization. This week's challenge is to use this maize color palette: https://github.com/AndiKur4/MaizePal

Prior to the Meetup, please make sure you have R downloaded on your computer (https://mirrors.nics.utk.edu/cran/). The free version of RStudio is recommended as well (https://rstudio.com/products/rstudio/download/). See you there!

title: Introduction to RStudio Cloud + R updates
description:
** If you have RSVP'd, check the email sent through Meetup with the Zoom link and some files (if needed) **

At this Meetup, we will talk about RStudio Cloud in general; a great online tool to get started with R, without having to install any software. We will also spend some time on how RStudio Cloud can be used for teaching, for the educators among us.
Lastly, we will talk about some of the changes that came with the latest release of R (4.0.2) - some of which are quite significant, and worth knowing about.
Schedule:
7.00 - 7.10 Introductions
7.10 - 7.20 RStudio Cloud (mostly for beginners)
7.20 - 7.40 RStudio Cloud for teaching
7.40 - 8.00 Latest R changes.

For beginners: we will not be doing an introduction to R at this meeting, but I'm sure we'll have plenty of people online to answer any questions.

** No need to download anything before this meeting **

Bring your pets, your kids, your room mates - everyone is welcome!
Can't wait to "see" you all!

title: Tidy Friday: Practicing Data Visualization in R
description:
Practice your data wrangling and visualization skills with other members of R-Ladies! During this virtual event, participants will report on their experience working on a shared dataset.

The R for Data Science Online Learning Community hosts a weekly "Tidy Tuesday" project in which they release a curated dataset every Tuesday for R users to practice data skills. We are meeting on Friday so that you have time to work on the dataset on your own.

How it works:

1. Read about the dataset here: https://github.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/blob/master/data/2020/2020-09-08/readme.md

2. Import the data into R using the instructions in the website above (we suggest using the code in the section titled "# Or read in the data manually")

3. Try to make a graph in R using the data. For some inspiration, search Twitter for #TidyTuesday.

4. Meet on Zoom during the event time. Message an organizer if you didn't receive the meeting password.

5. During the meeting, share your code and graph with the other participants using the "Share Screen" feature in Zoom or talk about where you got stuck and we'll work through it together.

Everyone's contribution is valuable, even if you're new to R! There are so many different ways to do things in R that your approach may be new to experienced R users.

title: Tidy Friday: Practicing Data Visualization in R
description:
Practice your data wrangling and visualization skills with other members of R-Ladies! During this virtual event, participants will report on their experience working on a shared dataset.

The R for Data Science Online Learning Community hosts a weekly "Tidy Tuesday" project in which they release a curated dataset every Tuesday for R users to practice data skills. We are meeting on Friday so that you have time to work on the dataset on your own.

How it works:

1. Read about the dataset here: https://github.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/blob/master/data/2020/2020-08-25/readme.md

2. Import the data into R using
chopped <- readr::read_tsv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2020/2020-08-25/chopped.tsv')

3. Try to make at least one graph in R using the data. For some inspiration, search Twitter for #TidyTuesday.

4. Meet on Zoom during the event time. Message an organizer if you didn't receive the meeting password.

5. During the meeting, share your code and graph with the other participants using the "Share Screen" feature in Zoom or talk about where you got stuck and we'll work through it together.

Everyone's contribution is valuable, even if you're new to R! There are so many different ways to do things in R that your approach may be new to experienced R users.

description:
Always wondered how to make interactive apps in R?

Mel Moreno will be presenting on how to create Shiny apps: she will take you through the basics, show how to create linear and multi-functional models, and eventually maps.
These are some of the Shiny apps Mel has made:
https://oysterprojectck.shinyapps.io/landing/ (landings for oyster project)

Also, want to hear about the conference experience or want tips on how to apply for a diversity scholarship? Next year's conference is in Orlando! We will be there to answer any questions and share the love for R.

title: Species distribution models in R
description:
Hey R-Ladies!

For this event, Dr. Lindsay Campbell, an assistant professor at the UF Florida Medical Entomology Laboratory, will be discussing her research interests and how she uses R for environmental data wrangling and species distribution models.

Should be a very nice lunch break with us! No prep needed for this meeting!

A zoom link will be sent on the day of the event to those who RSVP.

Image credit:
Campbell LP, Burkett-Cadena ND, Miqueli E, Unlu I, Sloyer KE, Medina J, Vasquez C, Petrie W, Reeves LE. Potential Distribution of Aedes (Ochlerotatus) scapularis (Diptera: Culicidae): A Vector Mosquito New to the Florida Peninsula. Insects. 2021; 12(3):213. https://doi.org/10.3390/insects12030213

title: Introduction to R Markdown
description:
Are you tired of copy-pasting information from R into Word documents?
Are you a newbie to R markdown and want to get started?
Have you already used R markdown but want to learn some new tricks?

If you answered yes, join us for our Introduction to R markdown presentation! We'll take an introductory tour of R markdown and then explore how to customize documents with figures, tables, automated figure and table numbering, literature citations, and more.

To follow along, we recommend having R and RStudio installed on your computer, as well as the following R packages: "rmarkdown," "tinytex," and "tidyverse."

We hope you will join us with your beveRage of choice and lots of R enthusiasm.

R-Ladies Gainesville welcomes members of all R proficiency levels, whether you're a new or aspiring R user, or an experienced R programmer interested in mentoring, networking & expert upskilling.

Please RSVP to receive the Zoom link before the event.

Please note:
In line with R-Ladies’ Mission Statement to encourage participation in the R community by underrepresented genders/identities (https://rladies.org/about-us/), our events are designed for those individuals (including, but not limited to cis/trans women, trans men, non-binary, genderqueer, agender). If you have any questions, please contact the event organizers.

title: Back to School 2021!
description:
We are back!!!

Pandemic fatigue has hit us hard, but we are ready to code again!

Join us for this 'Back to School' online event to get to know each other and once again, enjoy a Zoom call :p

R-Ladies Gainesville leadership will introduce themselves (and their favorite R packages) and we'll get to know each other over games (we look forward to mailing some stickers to the winners!).

We hope you will join us with your beveRage of choice and lots of R enthusiasm.

R-Ladies Gainesville welcomes members of all R proficiency levels, whether you're a new or aspiring R user, or an experienced R programmer interested in mentoring, networking & expert upskilling.

Please RSVP to receive the Zoom link before the event.

title: Creating your own interactive tutorials with `learnr`
description:
You can consider this a meta workshop. I will be giving a quick intro to the package 'learnr' and then go through the steps to get tutorials set up inside an R package, for use when giving workshops or organizing courses. Meetup will be recorded and files will be uploaded to github after the event.

UPDATE: I am so sorry everyone! Scheduling conflicts and family dynamics have been tough lately. Promise, this is the last change! :D

title: Create a resume in RMarkdown
description:
During this R-Ladies GNV meetup, Geraldine will introduce you to RMarkdown code to make a resume in R! During this show-and-tell, she will also cover some CSS and html basics required to create and customize certain components of the document.

If there is enough time, we'll also look at a few (academic) cv templates.

The code and files required will be available on our GitHub page (https://github.com/R-Ladies-Gainesville/tutorials) - check on Wednesday morning :)

RSVP for the Zoom link!

title: R tutorial series: Getting around GitHub
description:
Getting around GitHub can often be complicated to new users. Here we'll move into our R-Ladies Gainesville Tutorial Series with an introductory GitHub tutorial!

Michelle Slawinski ([https://github.com/slawinsm](https://github.com/slawinsm)) is going to guide us through how to use GitHub for version control and collaboration.

To participate, please complete the following before the event:
(1) create a GitHub account: [https://github.com/](https://github.com/)
(2) download and install Git: [https://github.com/git-guides/install-git](https://github.com/git-guides/install-git), more details [here](https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Getting-Started-Installing-Git)
(3) download and install GitHub Desktop: [https://desktop.github.com/](https://desktop.github.com/), more details [here](https://docs.github.com/en/desktop/installing-and-configuring-github-desktop/overview/getting-started-with-github-desktop)
Note: We will be available to help you at 11:45AM - EST. If you run into any issues with the steps above, just join the Zoom call early :)

title: Creating and sharing R tutorials
description:
Online R tutorials are some of the most effective ways to troubleshoot problems and learn new skills. While we may appreciate tutorials, it can be hard to prioritize making our own to share with the R community. In this meeting, we'll kick off the R-Ladies Gainesville Tutorial Series!

Do you have a solution to a tricky R problem? Is there an R package you've been wanting to learn? The Tutorial Series will provide a framework for formalizing your knowledge, sharing it with other R-Ladies, and getting feedback. We will provide an introduction to tutorials and discuss approaches to making your own.

To follow along, we recommend having R and RStudio installed on your computer, as well as the "rmarkdown" and "tidyverse" R packages.

title: New Year's SOCIAL
description:
We know - things have been terribly quiet on the R-Ladies front! That's about to change!
Please join us for a (very informal) social to chat about our R-Ladies chapter: let's reconnect and brainstorm about Meetup topics.

In an effort to make this event as inclusive as possible (i.e. family- and kid-friendly), we will meet at Boxcar, which is at Depot Park. Plenty of space for little ones to run around, plus a playground, and food options (Goldie's Burgers, Humble Wood Fire Pizza, and the Pop-A-Top General Store).

Bring all your positive vibes and great ideas: we look forward to seeing everyone again and starting off 2024 strong!
